Doctors said it was random, but I don't believe so. I worked on oil rigs & despite training hard/eating decent we partied excessively. Drinking, drugging, and long nights of insanity were the norm. The height of the oil boom & my health bust.

This circadian abuse factored into short circuiting my immune system causing it to replicate garbage white blood cells. I arrived at the ER with a WBC over 100,000, very little platelets, & just about dead.

You see a lot of people die on the cancer floors. You also see a lot of people eating garbage foods. I was fortunate to have been a athlete/bodybuilder since HS and grew up eating well. All things being equal, this is paramount.

The US has the best acute care in the world. Be aggressive & use it. After you live is where they seem to fall short. You will have complications. Doctors are conditioned to treat symptoms with pills & more pills for the side effects. I had a basket of pill bottles, wasting syndrome, & a dead left hip thanks to avascular necrosis caused by high dose prednisone. I eventually titrated off meds myself. The sad, boo hoo, self pitying patients seem to die a lot. Not saying the good humored don't, but we seem to fare far better. Feeling sorry for yourself is a waste of time & may lead to your demise.

Death is scary. Being a soft, whiny, why me, is even worse. It sucks, but find that silver lining & hold onto it to survive. Laugh, love, & live your life to the absolute fullest because, I promise you, tomorrow is never guaranteed.
